meta {
  name: POST SPIN response (step 2 of NA two-step SPIN handshake)
  type: http
  seq: 6
}

post {
  url: https://b-h-s.spr.{{country}}00.p.con-veh.net/ss/v1/user/{{user_id}}/spin
  body: json
  auth: bearer
}

auth:bearer {
  token: {{access_token}}
}

body:json {
  {
    "challenge": "{{spin_challenge_nonce}}",
    "response": "{{sha1_spin_plus_nonce_uppercase}}"
  }
}

headers {
  Accept: application/json
  Content-Type: application/json
  User-Agent: MyVW/1.0 Android
}

docs {
  v2.10.0 (Group C). VW North America SPIN response endpoint.

  Step 2 of the two-step SPIN flow. The client supplies the challenge
  nonce it received from ``/challenge`` plus the
  ``SHA1(SPIN + nonce).hexdigest().upper()`` digest. On success the
  backend returns a short-lived session token that must be sent as the
  ``X-Spin-Session`` header on the subsequent action POST.

  Response shape:

    {
      "data": {
        "sessionToken": "eyJ..."
      }
    }

  Defensive key-name variants observed: ``sessionToken`` /
  ``spinSessionToken`` / ``token``.

  NA-specific shape vs EU: EU does not have an analogue. The EU CARIAD-
  BFF either trusts the in-body SPIN field or relies on the OLA
  ``SecToken`` header issued during login. NA uses a per-action nonce
  to prevent SPIN replay across requests.

  Security note: ``SHA1`` is the protocol-mandated digest function for
  the backend handshake. It is NOT used as a cryptographic primitive
  in our own code path (a ``noqa: S324`` in the Python implementation
  documents this).
}
